<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18470920-2265">
               <interp inst="t18470920-2265" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18470920"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18470920-2265" type="date" value="18470920"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470920-2265-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2265-18470920 t18470920-2265-offence-1 t18470920-2265-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470920-2265-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-2265-18470920 t18470920-2265-offence-1 t18470920-2265-verdict-2"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470920-2265-charge-3" targOrder="Y" targets="def3-2265-18470920 t18470920-2265-offence-1 t18470920-2265-verdict-3"></join>
               <p>2265. <persName id="def1-2265-18470920" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2265-18470920" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2265-18470920" type="age" value="23"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2265-18470920" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2265-18470920" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">PETER TAYLOR. <persName id="def2-2265-18470920" type="defendantName">
                           <interp inst="def2-2265-18470920" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                           <interp inst="def2-2265-18470920" type="age" value="27"></interp>
                           <interp inst="def2-2265-18470920" type="surname" value="HEARN"></interp>
                           <interp inst="def2-2265-18470920" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS HEARN</persName>
                     </hi>
                  </persName>, and <persName id="def3-2265-18470920" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def3-2265-18470920" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-2265-18470920" type="age" value="29"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-2265-18470920" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-2265-18470920" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN ALLEN</hi>
                  </persName>, were indicted for<rs id="t18470920-2265-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470920-2265-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470920-2265-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> stealing 20 lbs. weight of lead, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18470920-name-1342" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1342" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1342" type="surname" value="HERRING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1342" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18470920-2265-offence-1 t18470920-name-1342"></join>Edward Herring</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RYLAND</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1343" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1343" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1343" type="surname" value="BAKER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1343" type="given" value="EDWIN"></interp>EDWIN BAKER.</persName>
                  </hi> I am manager to Mr. Edward Herring, of Trinity-street, St. Mary, Newington. He is a manufacturer of salphate of quinine—he has certain vessels in his manufactory lined with lead, which requires repairing from time to time—the prisoners were employed on the premises a few days ago—they were employed on Thursday the 9th, and of Friday the 10th of Sept.—I gave some directions to Smart and to Lomas—the prisoners left the premises about twenty minutes after five o'clock on Friday evening—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200226"></xptr>
               <p>followed them to the corner of Blackman-street—Trinity-street runs is to Blackman-street—Allen them remained behind with another plumber, and Taylor and Hearn crossed over to Suffolk-street—I should followed them—Hearn left Taylor and went along Suffolk-street, and Taylor commenced running up Blackman-street—I followed Taylor up a stable-yard, and in the yard I saw him take two pieces of lead out of his waistcoat-pocket, and throw them into a window, which was partly open; I laid hold of him—he had them one piece of lead in his hand—I took possession of that, and afterwards got the two pieces of lead from the window—there were about 20 bls. weight of it—it be<lb></lb>longed to Mr. Edward Herring—it had been on his premises.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long had Hearn and Allen been employed there? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Allen only the day previous, Hearn several times for about two months—there was nothing found on Hearn, or Allen, or at their lodging.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CAARTEEN.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Has Mr. Herring any partner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I have been there about eight months—it is called the "British and Foreign Alkali Company"—Mr. Herring centres in himself the whole of that body—he has told me so—I reside on the premises—Mr. Herring re<lb></lb>sides at Wandsworth—he attends to the business himself, as I do—I have never seen any partner but him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1344" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1344" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1344" type="surname" value="SMART"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1344" type="given" value="JAMES MOORE"></interp>JAMES MOORE SMART.</persName>
                  </hi> I took at Mr. Herring's manufactory. On Friday evening, the 10th of Sept., I watched the three prisoners—I went down stairs about ten minutes before five, and about five minutes before five o'clock Hearn came down—he took something off the right side of the bench in the plumbers' workshop, which appeared to be solder—he doubled it up, and put it into his left waistcoat pocket—he went away, and returned a second time—he bent up some piping, or some sheet lead, I cannot swear which, and secreted that about his person—he went away, and come back the third time—he than beat up some sheet lead, and placed it under his waistcoat—while he was so doing Taylor came down—he beat up three pieces of sheet lead, and placed them under his waistcoat—then Allen came down—he beat up two pieces of sheet lead, and placed them under his waistcoat—they then went up stairs—I went up as quick as I could, and ordered the people in the warehouse to shut the gates, but the prisoners were gone out—I and Bake followed Taylor—I saw him taken in the yard by Baker—I saw Baker pick up one piece of lead—I saw Taylor give Baker one piece, and one piece to Lomas—of course it was lead taken from my master's premises—he went to no other place, because Mr. Baker was after him—I took Allen; he said he knew nothing of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where were you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In the wine-cellar, about twenty yards from the workshop—it is under the warehouse, but in a line with the plumbers' shop—I looked through the open—work of the door—it is a kind of grating—there is about two inches space between each bar—I saw Hearn take something that seemed to he solder, but I cannot say what—Taylor come down while Hearn was down the third time—he beat up three pieces of lead, and placed them under his waistcoat—the prisoners were all together before they went away, but they came in one at a time—Allen was taken the same evening at his own door—no property was found on him, or at his house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see Allen do anything? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, beat up two pieces of lead, and place them under his waistcoat—Hearn was in there three separate times, and the last time he was in, Taylor came, and directly after<lb></lb>wards Allen came in—they could see one another take it.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200227"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CAARTEEN.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Who came first into the shop? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Hearn—I do not knew where the other two prisoners were at the time Hearn took what I considered to be solder—Hearn then left, and came again, and beat up something—I cannot say whether it was piping or sheet lead—neither of the other prisoners were there then—Hearn went away, and came again the third time, and beat up some sheet lead—while he was there Taylor and Allen came—the place is about ten feet long, and eight feet, wide—the man had done work at that time—the prisoners were as near together as they could be—the sheet lead is on the side of the workshop, they were all three at that lead.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1345" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1345" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1345" type="surname" value="LOMAS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1345" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES LOMAS.</persName>
                  </hi> I am in Mr. Herring's service. On Friday afternoon, the 10th of Sept., Mr. Baker told me to watch—I watched, and saw Hearn take two pieces of leaden pipe, about nine inches long—he placed them about his body, and went away—he came back again, and took a piece of sheet lead, he beat it together, and put that about his body, under his waistcoat—he went out, and came in the third time, took some more lead, beat it together, and placed that about his body—Taylor then came in, beat up three pieces of lead, and placed it about his body—I did not see Allen come in, for I left Hearn and Taylor in the room when I went up into the warehouse to give Information to a man to go for a policemen—I then went and watched again—I saw the three prisoners together in the room—they were standing together, and feeling one another down, to see whether they would be noticed in going out—they than came up stairs, and went out—I followed them to the bottom of Trinity-street—they crossed, and Taylor turned towards St. George's Church—I saw Baker run after him—I followed him—he turned down a stable-yard, and there threw away some lead.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1346" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1346" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1346" type="surname" value="WALKER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1346" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES WALKER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant, M</hi> 18.) On Friday, the 10th of Sept, Taylor was given into my charge, and this lead was brought to the station by Mr. Baker—Taylor said the foremen give him the lead to take to the shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1347" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1347" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1347" type="surname" value="GOLDIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1347" type="given" value="JOSHUA"></interp>JOSHUA GOLDIN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman M</hi> 87.) I took Hearn that evening in Bedford<lb></lb>bury—I told him what it was for; he said he knew nothing at all of it—I told him I took on a charge of stealing lead from Mr. Herring's premises, where he had been working that day—he said he knew nothing about stealing lead, but he knew there was something up when he saw them following them.</p>
               <p>(The prisoners received good characters.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">TAYLOR</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18470920-2265-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
